{"key":"processedPost-16029674","value":{"id":16029674,"first":16029586,"last":16036425,"when":1333314651,"utime":"04/02/12 12:10 AM","content":"<img src='/forums/images/moved.gif'> <b>This thread was moved from Advanced Mycology.</b><br /><br />Reason:<br />Off topic in advanced mycology.<br /><br />We've known for a long time that it's best to allow a 'rest' between flushes to allow the mycelium to consume a bit more of the substrate.&nbsp; This is why we allow a substrate to slightly dry out for a week or so before re-hydrating for the next flush.<br /><br />Straws are a lame way to supply moisture.&nbsp; Soaking is superior, as is placing the cake in a saucer of water for a few hours, which can be done mid-flush if necessary.<br /><br />Mycelium consumes solid food, so there's no nutrients you could add to the soak water which would help.<br /><br />I'm a retired mechanical and electrical engineer.&nbsp; Both come in handy building stuff.<br />RR","title":"Re: Delaying Flushes (moved)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}